  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Can magnesium glycinate help with sleep?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Yes, magnesium glycinate is one of the most evidence-based natural sleep aids available. Magnesium activates the parasympathetic nervous system (the "rest and digest" system), binds to GABA receptors to promote relaxation, and helps regulate melatonin production. A 2012 study in the Journal of Research in Medical Sciences found that magnesium supplementation (500mg daily for 8 weeks) significantly improved sleep quality scores, sleep time, sleep efficiency, and melatonin concentration in elderly subjects. The glycine component adds further sleep benefit — a 2006 study in Sleep and Biological Rhythms found that 3g of glycine before bed improved subjective sleep quality and reduced daytime sleepiness.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Does magnesium glycinate cause diarrhea?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Magnesium glycinate is the form least likely to cause digestive side effects. Magnesium oxide and magnesium citrate have strong osmotic laxative effects — they draw water into the intestines, frequently causing diarrhea, cramping, and urgency. Magnesium glycinate is chelated (bound to an amino acid), which means it is absorbed primarily through amino acid transport pathways rather than osmotic mechanisms. This results in higher absorption with significantly less unabsorbed magnesium reaching the colon. For individuals who have experienced GI side effects with other magnesium forms, glycinate is the recommended alternative.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What is the difference between magnesium glycinate and magnesium citrate?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Magnesium glycinate and magnesium citrate differ in absorption mechanism, bioavailability, GI tolerance, and secondary benefits. Glycinate is chelated to the amino acid glycine, absorbed through amino acid transport pathways, causes minimal GI effects, and provides calming glycine benefits. Citrate is bound to citric acid, has good bioavailability but works partly through osmotic mechanisms in the gut, commonly causes loose stools and diarrhea, and may be beneficial for constipation relief. For sleep, anxiety, and stress: choose glycinate. For constipation: citrate may be preferable. For general magnesium supplementation with minimal GI effects: glycinate is superior.' } },
