      <span class="key-stat-num">50%</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">Of American adults are magnesium deficient according to USDA data. Yet magnesium oxide — the cheapest and most common supplement form — has only <strong>4% bioavailability</strong>. Magnesium glycinate absorption rates range from 20 to 30%, making it 5 to 7 times more effective per milligram.</p>
    </div>

    <p>The glycinate advantage is twofold. First, the glycine amino acid acts as a molecular carrier, facilitating magnesium absorption through amino acid transport pathways in the small intestine — a fundamentally different and more efficient mechanism than the passive diffusion that oxide and carbonate forms rely on. Second, glycine itself is an inhibitory neurotransmitter that binds to NMDA and glycine receptors in the brain, promoting relaxation, improving sleep quality, and reducing anxiety. This means magnesium glycinate delivers both the magnesium you need and a calming amino acid in the same molecule.</p>

