    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Magnesium Glycinate Gummies</h2>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Why is magnesium glycinate better than other forms?</summary><p>Higher bioavailability (20-30% vs. 4% for oxide), gentlest on digestion (minimal GI side effects), and dual benefit from glycine's calming neurotransmitter effects. The superior form for sleep, stress, and sensitive stomachs.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How much magnesium glycinate should adults take?</summary><p>RDA is 310-420mg depending on age and sex. Most gummies provide 100-250mg elemental magnesium. For sleep and stress, 200-400mg in the evening is common. The supplemental upper limit is 350mg. Most adults need 200-300mg to fill dietary gaps.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can magnesium glycinate help with sleep?</summary><p>Yes. Magnesium activates GABA receptors and regulates melatonin. A 2012 study found 500mg daily improved sleep quality, time, and melatonin levels. Glycine independently improves sleep quality through NMDA receptor modulation.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Does magnesium glycinate cause diarrhea?</summary><p>Magnesium glycinate is the form least likely to cause diarrhea. It absorbs through amino acid pathways with minimal osmotic effects, unlike citrate and oxide which draw water into the intestines.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Glycinate vs. citrate: what is the difference?</summary><p>Glycinate: highest absorption, gentlest on gut, calming glycine benefits — best for sleep and stress. Citrate: good absorption but osmotic laxative effect — better for constipation. For general supplementation: glycinate is superior.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can you take magnesium glycinate with other supplements?</summary><p>Pairs well with vitamin D3, B vitamins, L-theanine, and melatonin. Take 2+ hours apart from calcium, tetracycline antibiotics, and bisphosphonates due to absorption competition.</p></details>

